Boil your #kettle{} and pour the water into a large #saucepan{} on high heat. Add @salt{1/2%tsp}. When boiling, stir in the @rigatoni pasta{200%g} and cook for ~{12%minutes}. Drain in a #colander{}, pop back in the pan, drizzle with a little @oil{a little} and stir through to stop it sticking together. Leave to the side.

Meanwhile, trim the @courgette{1}, halve lengthways and slice into 1cm half moons. Roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}(roughly chopped) (stalks and all). Zest and halve the @lemon{1/2}(zested and halved). Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a garlic press).

Heat a large #frying pan{} on high heat (no oil) and add the courgette. Cook, until starting to brown, ~{3-4%minutes} on each side. Add the garlic and cook, stirring, for ~{1%minute}.

Once the courgettes are browned, reduce the heat and add the @creme fraiche{150%g}, @water{100%ml} and @vegetable stock powder{1} to the pan. Season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}. Stir together, bring to a simmer and cook until the sauce has thickened slightly, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Stir the @king prawns{150%g} into the sauce and continue to simmer until the prawns are cooked through, ~{4-5%minutes}. IMPORTANT: The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle. Add a splash of water if the sauce is a bit thick. Meanwhile, mix together the lemon zest and remaining parsley in a #small bowl{}.

Toss the drained pasta into the sauce. Add a squeeze of lemon juice to taste. Season with salt and pepper to taste, then serve in #bowls{} topped with the lemon zest and parsley mix. Enjoy!

> The delicious creaminess of crème fraîche makes it the perfect thing to use in pasta sauces like this one. This dish uses ingredients like juicy prawns, parsley, courgette and lemon for a fresh result that won't disappoint.